Level-0 Motion: This House Supports Green Central Banking., Side: for
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Central banks are uniquely positioned to address the climate crisis.", "argument": ["The world is facing a climate disaster with wildfires, floods, and unmet environmental promises.", "Immediate and decisive action is needed.", "Central banks are uniquely positioned to take this action.", "Institutions like the World Bank and IMF already emphasize green investment, indicating this isn't a radical shift.", "Central banks have historically prioritized issues like unemployment, inflation, and financial stability, and should now prioritize the planet's survival."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Government-led action on climate change is flawed due to political influence, budget limitations, and slow implementation.", "argument": ["Government-led action is subject to political influence and lobbying, leading to suboptimal investments.", "Limited government budgets force trade-offs that can hurt social welfare programs and fuel climate denialism.", "Government action is too slow to address the urgent climate crisis."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Private actors are better positioned to drive green tech innovation due to profit potential, lower barriers to entry, economies of agglomeration, and the attraction of innovators.", "argument": ["Immense profit potential in the green tech market.", "Lower barriers to entry due to previous government subsidies.", "Economies of agglomeration allow companies to learn from each other.", "Profit motive and the 'vanity project' aspect attract innovators.", "Government focus on incentivizing green production ignores the role of private actors."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Forced divestment undermines political action on climate change by creating the illusion of action and shifting lobbying efforts.", "argument": ["Forced divestment creates the illusion of action.", "It saps political will for genuine measures like regulation and carbon taxes.", "Monetary policy is slow, indirect, and limited.", "Lobbying will shift to central banks, hindering real change."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Green central banking can rapidly funnel capital into the green sector.", "argument": ["Central banks can use asset purchasing programs, adjusted banking rates, and control over bank liquidity to direct capital to the green sector.", "This incentivizes the development of affordable green goods.", "It stimulates private investment through a signaling effect.", "It pressures existing industries to transition to sustainable practices.", "It generates jobs, especially in underserved areas and developing nations.", "Large corporations rely heavily on borrowed capital.", "Increasing borrowing costs makes current practices less profitable.", "This forces companies to adapt and invest in greener technologies.", "Client relationships with investment banks are crucial, so companies face the same regulations even if they seek other lenders.", "The policy attracts major investors like private equity and pension funds.", "Signaling central bank support increases the attractiveness and stability of green investments.", "This funnels capital into sustainable technologies.", "This redirects private investment away from polluting industries towards green alternatives.", "The policy incentivizes the development and implementation of existing green technologies.", "This aligns private and social interests.", "Consumers care about the service, not the source.", "This allows companies like Rio Tinto to transition to cleaner production.", "Central banks can adjust interest rates and influence investment.", "Central banks can incentivize green technologies and disincentivize polluting industries.", "Central bank intervention directly addresses the problem.", "Central bank action can facilitate the transition away from exploitative industries in the developing world.", "Example: Singapore's development without natural resources."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Shifting central bank incentives away from fossil fuel industries will create a devastating short-term shock, leading to widespread job losses and economic hardship, especially in developing nations.", "argument": ["Many industries, especially in developing nations, rely on fossil fuels.", "Shifting central bank incentives will create a short-term shock.", "This will lead to widespread job losses and economic hardship.", "These industries lack the resources to rapidly diversify.", "Cutting off capital flow will prevent their eventual transition.", "Forcing job losses for a speculative long-term benefit is unacceptable."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "The opponent's arguments about green investments and job losses are contradictory.", "argument": ["The opponents claim current green investments are sufficient.", "The opponents argue that only their policy can prevent job losses.", "These two claims are contradictory.", "If green technology is developing rapidly enough, their policy is unnecessary.", "If green technology isn't developing rapidly enough, their job loss predictions are inaccurate."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "Large companies have the resources to diversify but prioritize short-term profits.", "argument": ["The opponents claim large companies lack the resources to diversify.", "Companies like Rio Tinto and Shell have vast resources and green technology patents.", "These companies prioritize short-term profits over social good.", "The proposed policy incentivizes private interests to align with the social imperative."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "Similar policy shifts have occurred before, and any potential inflation is a worthwhile trade-off for sustainable jobs.", "argument": ["Similar policy shifts have occurred before.", "Expert investors will understand the shift in asset purchasing.", "Any potential inflation is a worthwhile trade-off for sustainable jobs.", "The policy is unlikely to cause severe inflation because it doesn't represent a major change in the market.", "The plan fosters long-term, sustainable employment."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "The opponent's reliance on speculative green investment is insufficient and fails to address the collective action problem.", "argument": ["The opponent's reliance on speculative green investment is insufficient.", "Speculative green investment is a small percentage of portfolios.", "The opponents fail to address the collective action problem faced by developing nations.", "The proposed policy provides long-term solutions.", "Even successful speculative investments would decimate jobs in fossil fuel industries, proving the opponent's internal contradiction.", "The proposed policy prioritizes preventing climate catastrophe over preserving jobs in polluting industries."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "Restructuring costs and job losses are already realities in the status quo, and transitioning to sustainable industries offers a chance for improvement.", "argument": ["Restructuring costs and job losses are already happening.", "Coal mines exploit workers with unsafe conditions and low wages.", "Transitioning to sustainable industries offers a chance for improvement."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Green tech is already attractive due to growth potential, declining costs, government investment, first-mover advantage, and positive PR, making capital availability not the limiting factor.", "argument": ["Green tech has massive growth potential.", "Production costs are declining due to R&D.", "There is substantial government investment in green tech.", "First-mover advantage attracts investment.", "Positive PR attracts investment.", "The limiting factor is the pace of technological advancement, not capital availability."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Divestment will push capital towards neutral sectors like pharmaceuticals or tech, not necessarily green initiatives.", "argument": ["Divestment leads to portfolio diversification.", "Capital will flow to stable, low-risk sectors like pharmaceuticals or tech.", "This won't necessarily stimulate green investment."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Developing nations rely on high-polluting industries for economic growth and FDI, and this motion removes those incentives.", "argument": ["Developing nations rely on high-polluting industries for economic growth.", "FDI is attracted by access to natural resources and less stringent regulations.", "The motion removes incentives for FDI, crippling economic growth."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "The scale of the proposed economic restructuring will trigger inflation that central banks cannot control.", "argument": ["Opponents believe inflation is manageable due to historical precedent and central bank expertise.", "The scale of the proposed economic restructuring is being ignored.", "The plan relies on changing investor expectations, which will trigger inflation.", "Central banks cannot prevent harmful decisions by individual companies."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Restructuring to cut costs will disproportionately harm vulnerable workers.", "argument": ["Even in the best-case scenario, companies will restructure to cut costs.", "Vulnerable workers, the lowest-paid, and those with the least bargaining power will suffer most.", "This is a predictable outcome of prioritizing rapid economic upheaval.", "The opponent's plan exacerbates this harm."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Green central banking is economically beneficial, fostering innovation, creating jobs, and mitigating long-term economic risks of climate change.", "argument": ["Green central banking fosters innovation.", "It creates jobs.", "It mitigates the long-term economic risks of climate change, such as disruptions to production, agriculture, and labor markets.", "It protects the economy and ensures a sustainable future."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Addressing the scale of production is crucial because even less environmentally damaging production can still cause significant harm when scaled up massively.", "argument": ["The core issue is the increase in production, not just the type of technology used.", "Even 'greener' production can cause harm when scaled up.", "Zero-impact production has not been achieved yet.", "Incentivizing greener production without addressing the scale of production is insufficient."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Developing nations rely on high-polluting industries for economic growth and FDI, and this motion removes those incentives.", "argument": ["Developing nations rely on high-polluting industries for economic growth.", "FDI is attracted by access to natural resources and less stringent regulations.", "The motion removes incentives for FDI, crippling economic growth."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Companies facing divestment pressure will prioritize cost-cutting and worker exploitation over transitioning to green technologies.", "argument": ["Divestment pressure leads to cost-cutting.", "Companies will prioritize cost-cutting over green transitions.", "This results in worker exploitation and abuse."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Central banks are the only effective actors to address the climate crisis.", "argument": ["The central bank is the only effective actor.", "Opponents rely on private sector investment and political action, which are flawed."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Political action is ineffective due to corporate lobbying and lack of political will.", "argument": ["Corporate lobbying cripples meaningful legislation.", "Lack of political will is demonstrated by the sidelining of the Green New Deal.", "Minor policies are insufficient to address structural issues.", "Politicizing environmental policy risks backsliding and repeal (example: Obamacare)."]}

